name\": \"CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs on the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate via surface-bound CO\u2082\u207b\u2022 intermediate. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the high H\u2082 fugacity of alkaline vents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally under simulated hydrothermal conditions (Preiner et al., 2020; Roldan et al., 2015). The structural analogy between greigite and biological ferredoxin [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters supports this as a primordial carbon fixation step (Russell & Martin, 2004). Herschy et al. (2014) showed formate production in simulated alkaline vent reactors.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with native iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions provided by serpentinization-derived H\u2082 and Fe\u2070\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on magnetite/Fe\u2070 surfaces via Fischer-Tropsch-type mechanism. Fe\u2070 serves as a strong reductant, donating electrons to reduce the C=O bond of formate to formaldehyde. The reaction proceeds through a surface-bound formyl intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite surfaces can reduce C1 oxygenates further (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Reduction of formate/CO to formaldehyde-level intermediates on iron-bearing mineral surfaces has been proposed as a key step in prebiotic carbon chain elongation (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). Fe\u2070 is a thermodynamically strong reductant capable of driving this reduction under hydrothermal conditions (Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-type aldol dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay with borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline aqueous pool, pH 10-11, Ca(OH)\u2082 as base, borate stabilizes intermediates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol addition. One formaldehyde undergoes umpolung via a Cannizzaro-like enolization to generate a nucleophilic carbanion equivalent, which attacks the second formaldehyde electrophile. Borate minerals complex with the resulting glycolaldehyde diol, stabilizing the product against further Cannizzaro degradation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The initial step of the formose reaction generating glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is well-established (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). Borate minerals stabilize sugar products by complexing with cis-diols, preventing sugar degradation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate and orient reactants (Ferris et al., 1996). Glycolaldehyde has been identified as a key interstellar and prebiotic molecule (Hollis et al., 2000).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Slightly alkaline conditions, pH 9-10, borate stabilization of product\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde enolizes under basic conditions, generating a nucleophilic enediol. This carbanion attacks formaldehyde to form a new C\u2013C bond, yielding glyceraldehyde. Borate complexation of the product cis-diol stabilizes glyceraldehyde against retroaldol and epimerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the second step of the formose reaction, well-characterized in the literature (Breslow, 1959; Kopetzki & Antonietti, 2011). Borate stabilization of glyceraldehyde is critical for selective sugar synthesis (Ricardo et al., 2004; Kim et al., 2011). This step extends the carbon chain from C2 to C3, setting up the key methylglyoxal intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on iron minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Native iron and sulfide minerals present, serpentinization-derived H\u2082, slightly alkaline pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 undergoes stepwise reduction and C\u2013C bond formation on mixed iron oxide-sulfide mineral surfaces. Three CO\u2082 equivalents are reduced and coupled via surface-bound C1 intermediates (formate \u2192 formyl \u2192 CO), forming a C3 skeleton. The terminal carboxylation and keto group formation yields pyruvate. The mechanism parallels the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway in reverse.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on native iron and iron mineral surfaces has been demonstrated experimentally (Cody et al., 2000; Varma et al., 2018). Muchowska et al. (2017) showed that Fe\u2070 can drive the formation of pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids from CO\u2082 under mild aqueous conditions. This reaction is a cornerstone of the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082) surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Thermal decarboxylation facilitated by mineral surface and elevated temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes non-oxidative thermal decarboxylation. The \u03b2-keto acid functional group facilitates loss of CO\u2082 through a cyclic transition state, yielding acetaldehyde. Pyrite surface Lewis acid sites coordinate the keto and carboxylate oxygens, lowering the activation barrier for decarboxylation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids is well-known in organic chemistry and proceeds readily at hydrothermal temperatures (Cooper et al., 2011). Cody et al. (2004) demonstrated pyruvate decarboxylation in hydrothermal systems. Pyrite surfaces catalyze various organic transformations through Lewis acid interactions (Schoonen et al., 1999). This reaction connects the C3 hub pyruvate to the C2 hub acetaldehyde, a critical network link.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Dehydration of glyceraldehyde to methylglyoxal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly acidic conditions, pH 4-6, UV irradiation, wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes acid-catalyzed elimination of water. The C2 hydroxyl is lost via E1cb mechanism, forming an enol intermediate that tautomerizes to methylglyoxal (2-oxopropanal). TiO\u2082 photocatalysis may generate reactive oxygen species that facilitate the oxidative dehydration. Clay surface acidity promotes the elimination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyceraldehyde dehydration to methylglyoxal is thermodynamically favorable and occurs under mildly acidic conditions at elevated temperatures (Thornalley, 1996). Methylglyoxal is a well-known product of sugar degradation in the formose reaction (Benner et al., 2012). This transformation is critical for converting the C3 sugar into a C3 dicarbonyl that serves as the direct precursor to lactaldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on mackinawite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Selective ketone reduction favored over aldehyde reduction on FeS surface due to steric and electronic selectivity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Methylglyoxal adsorbs on the mackinawite (FeS) surface via the more electrophilic ketone carbonyl. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing surface-bound hydride. Selective transfer of hydride to the ketone C=O yields the secondary alcohol, producing lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) while preserving the aldehyde functionality. The FeS surface provides chemoselective reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Mackinawite (FeS) is an effective hydrogenation catalyst under hydrothermal conditions (Rickard & Luther, 2007). Selective reduction of ketones over aldehydes on mineral surfaces has been proposed based on differential binding affinities (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998). The selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde is the key step enabling the Strecker route to threonine. FeS-catalyzed reductions of carbonyl compounds under hydrothermal conditions are well-documented (Heinen & Lauwers, 1996).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetaldehyde oxidative hydroxylation to methylglyoxal via UV photocatalysis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), no ozone shield on early Earth, apatite mineral surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde and formaldehyde undergo a UV-photocatalyzed cross-aldol condensation on TiO\u2082 surface, followed by oxidation. TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs under UV, producing hydroxyl radicals. Acetaldehyde enolizes and attacks formaldehyde to give 3-hydroxypropanal, which is then oxidized at C1 by TiO\u2082-generated radical species to yield methylglyoxal. Alternatively, acetaldehyde is directly photo-oxidized and then reacts with formaldehyde-derived radicals.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalysis is highly relevant on early Earth where intense UV radiation penetrated the anoxic atmosphere (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). Cross-aldol reactions between C1 and C2 aldehydes are thermodynamically favorable (Kopetzki & Antonietti, 2011). This provides a convergent second route to methylglyoxal from hydrothermal-derived acetaldehyde and formaldehyde, linking hydrothermal outputs to surface photochemistry. Photo-oxidation of organic molecules on TiO\u2082 is well-established (Hoffmann et al., 1995).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mild aqueous conditions, pH 7-9, concentrated evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base) via nucleophilic addition-elimination. The imine is then attacked by cyanide (HCN) in a nucleophilic addition, forming 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (the \u03b1-aminonitrile of threonine). Clay surfaces concentrate reactants and template the reaction through surface adsorption. The hydroxyl group at C3 remains intact throughout.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is the most well-established prebiotic route to amino acids (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957). Formation of \u03b1-aminonitriles from aldehydes, ammonia, and HCN proceeds efficiently under mild aqueous conditions. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes and concentrates these reactions (Ferris, 2005). The use of lactaldehyde as the starting aldehyde specifically yields the threonine \u03b1-aminonitrile (Lerner et al., 1993). This is the most direct prebiotic route to threonine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous solution, mildly acidic to neutral pH, prolonged heating or UV-assisted hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis. First, water attacks the nitrile carbon to form an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide). Second, the amide undergoes further hydrolysis to yield the free carboxylic acid, releasing ammonia. This yields threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid). The reaction is accelerated by mild heating and acidic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is a fundamental aqueous reaction and the final step of the Strecker synthesis (Strecker, 1850). Under prebiotic conditions, aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds at moderate rates at pH 4-7 and temperatures above 300K (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). This step converts the Strecker aminonitrile intermediate into the final amino acid product. The reaction requires no special catalysis beyond aqueous solution and mild heating.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid, high H\u2082 fugacity, mineral surface catalysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-keto acid 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base) at the C2 keto position. The imine is then reduced by H\u2082 dissociated on the FeS mineral surface, yielding threonine. The FeS surface acts as a heterogeneous hydrogenation catalyst, facilitating both imine formation and reduction in a one-pot reductive amination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is a well-established prebiotic route to amino acids, mimicking extant transamination biochemistry (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). FeS minerals catalyze reductive amination under hydrothermal conditions, as demonstrated for pyruvate \u2192 alanine (Muchowska et al., 2019; Barge et al., 2019). Application to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate yields threonine directly, providing an alternative to the Strecker route. This pathway is thermodynamically favorable under reducing hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidative carboxylation of methylglyoxal to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, hydrated CO\u2082 (bicarbonate), mineral pool setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Methylglyoxal undergoes selective hydration at the ketone to form the 2,2-dihydroxy intermediate. UV-driven TiO\u2082 photocatalysis generates reactive carboxylating species from dissolved CO\u2082/bicarbonate. Radical carboxylation at the aldehyde terminus or nucleophilic carboxylation of the hydrated intermediate inserts a CO\u2082-derived carboxyl group, forming 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate. The reaction is analogous to \u03b1-ketoglutarate formation from succinate semialdehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Photochemical carboxylation reactions are plausible under early Earth UV conditions (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). TiO\u2082-driven CO\u2082 fixation into organic molecules has been demonstrated experimentally (Inoue et al., 1979). The formation of \u03b1-keto acids from shorter-chain aldehydes and CO\u2082 provides a surface-environment pathway to the threonine precursor keto acid, complementing the hydrothermal Strecker route. This is a speculative but thermodynamically feasible connection necessary to complete the reductive amination pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde from CO\u2082 and H\u2082\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with native iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on Fe\u2070 surfaces. CO and H\u2082 undergo Fischer-Tropsch-type chain growth on magnetite surfaces via a carbide or formyl insertion mechanism. Sequential hydrogenation and chain extension produces C2 oxygenates. Acetaldehyde is a primary C2 product of FTT synthesis, formed via surface-bound acetyl intermediate hydrogenation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces in hydrothermal systems has been extensively studied (McCollom et al., 1999; McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Acetaldehyde is among the observed C2 oxygenate products. Foustoukos & Seyfried (2004) demonstrated FTT synthesis of short-chain organics under seafloor hydrothermal conditions. This provides a direct hydrothermal route to acetaldehyde independent of pyruvate decarboxylation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydrolysis and photochemical reduction to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 and MoS\u2082 photocatalysts\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic chemistry conditions, early Earth atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes UV-assisted hydrolysis: HCN + H\u2082O \u2192 formamide (HCONH\u2082) under UV irradiation. Formamide is then photolytically reduced on TiO\u2082/MoS\u2082 surfaces, losing NH\u2083 and gaining H to yield formaldehyde. Alternatively, HCN photohydration proceeds directly to a formaldehyde-imine which hydrolyzes. This cyanosulfidic photochemistry links the HCN pool to the aldehyde pool.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The photochemical conversion of HCN to formaldehyde and other C1 species via formamide intermediate is part of the Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). UV photolysis of HCN solutions produces formamide and other products (Ferris & Hagan, 1984). TiO\u2082 and MoS\u2082 photocatalysis can drive these transformations under prebiotically relevant UV fluxes. This reaction provides a surface-environment route to formaldehyde complementary to the hydrothermal formate reduction pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol-Tishchenko disproportionation of glycolaldehyde to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with apatite mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline aqueous conditions pH 9-10, evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde enolizes under basic conditions on the montmorillonite surface. The enolate attacks the aldehyde of glycolaldehyde in a cross-aldol addition, forming a C4 diol-aldehyde intermediate (4-hydroxy-2-hydroxymethyl-butanal). The intermediate undergoes retro-aldol/isomerization on the mineral surface to yield lactaldehyde and formaldehyde, driven by the thermodynamic stability of the products. Alternatively, direct cross-aldol gives 2-hydroxybutanal which can isomerize on the clay surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cross-aldol reactions between C2 aldehydes are fundamental in formose-type chemistry (Breslow, 1959). Montmorillonite clay catalyzes aldol condensations and controls product selectivity through surface templating (Ferris, 2005). The formation of C3 branched and hydroxylated aldehydes from C2 precursors is well-precedented in formose chemistry. This provides a second surface-based route to lactaldehyde directly from two hydrothermal products (glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde), bypassing the methylglyoxal intermediate.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Primary Strecker route via hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"The longest and most detailed pathway. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde dimerizes to glycolaldehyde on surface clays, which combines with more formaldehyde to form glyceraldehyde. Glyceraldehyde dehydrates to methylglyoxal, which is selectively reduced to lactaldehyde at hydrothermal vents. Strecker synthesis with NH\u2083 and HCN gives the aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker route via FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis directly produces acetaldehyde from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 in hydrothermal vents. Acetaldehyde and formaldehyde undergo UV-photocatalyzed cross-aldol/oxidation to methylglyoxal on surfaces. Methylglyoxal is reduced to lactaldehyde at vents, followed by Strecker synthesis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker route via pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is synthesized directly from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on iron minerals. It undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde at hydrothermal vents. Acetaldehyde and formaldehyde form methylglyoxal photocatalytically, then methylglyoxal is reduced to lactaldehyde. Strecker synthesis completes the threonine pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination route via methylglyoxal carboxylation\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formaldehyde via formate. Formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal in surface environments. Methylglyoxal is photochemically carboxylated to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate. Reductive amination on FeS surfaces at hydrothermal vents yields threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination via acetaldehyde-derived methylglyoxal carboxylation\",\n      \"description\": \"FTT synthesis gives acetaldehyde; hydrothermal formate reduction gives formaldehyde. UV-photocatalytic cross-aldol produces methylglyoxal, which is carboxylated to the \u03b1-keto acid and reductively aminated to threonine at vents.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-photochemical formaldehyde route to Strecker threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is photochemically hydrolyzed to formaldehyde on TiO\u2082 surfaces. Formaldehyde enters the formose pathway to glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde. Strecker synthesis uses HCN and NH\u2083 to complete threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-aldol lactaldehyde route from glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde (surface). FTT synthesis gives acetaldehyde (hydrothermal). Cross-aldol disproportionation of glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde on clay gives lactaldehyde directly. Strecker synthesis yields threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde cross-aldol to lactaldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is formed hydrothermally and decarboxylated to acetaldehyde. Formaldehyde dimerizes to glycolaldehyde. Cross-aldol of glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde on clay yields lactaldehyde. Strecker gives threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-derived formaldehyde to reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN photochemically produces formaldehyde. Formaldehyde builds up to glyceraldehyde via formose steps, dehydrates to methylglyoxal, which is carboxylated to the \u03b1-keto acid. Reductive amination gives threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed FTT-acetaldehyde and pyruvate decarboxylation convergent methylglyoxal route\",\n      \"description\": \"Both FTT synthesis (rxn_014) and pyruvate decarboxylation (rxn_005 \u2192 rxn_006) produce acetaldehyde, which converges at the methylglyoxal node via photocatalytic cross-aldol with HCN-derived formaldehyde (rxn_015). Methylglyoxal is reduced to lactaldehyde, and Strecker synthesis gives threonine. This pathway demonstrates maximal convergence of hydrothermal and surface chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde - key C1 building block formed by two routes and consumed by four reactions\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde - C2 hub produced by two distinct hydrothermal routes, consumed by two surface reactions\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Methylglyoxal - critical C3 dicarbonyl intermediate where sugar chemistry and aldehyde chemistry converge, feeds both Strecker and reductive amination routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde - penultimate Strecker aldehyde formed by two reduction/aldol routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"description\": \"Threonine - target molecule formed by two independent final reactions (Strecker hydrolysis and reductive amination)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "Threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid) is synthesized through a convergent prebiotic network originating from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 in hydrothermal environments, progressing through C1-C3 aldehyde intermediates in surface environments, and culminating in Strecker synthesis and reductive amination routes in surface/biochemical settings. The network leverages formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and pyruvate as hub molecules. Lactaldehyde is the key penultimate aldehyde for the Strecker route, formed via methylglyoxal reduction or cross-aldol chemistry. An alternative route proceeds through the \u03b1-keto acid 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoate and reductive amination. Multiple environmental pathways intersect to provide robust, redundant routes to threonine under early Earth conditions.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "Formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "Glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "Acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "Glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanal", "common_name": "Methylglyoxal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h3H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "Lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2-3,4H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "Threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "Threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs on the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate via surface-bound CO\u2082\u207b\u2022 intermediate. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the high H\u2082 fugacity of alkaline vents.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally under simulated hydrothermal conditions (Preiner et al., 2020; Roldan et al., 2015). The structural analogy between greigite and biological ferredoxin [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters supports this as a primordial carbon fixation step (Russell & Martin, 2004). Herschy et al. (2014) showed formate production in simulated alkaline vent reactors."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with native iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Reducing conditions provided by serpentinization-derived H\u2082 and Fe\u2070"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on magnetite/Fe\u2070 surfaces via Fischer-Tropsch-type mechanism. Fe\u2070 serves as a strong reductant, donating electrons to reduce the C=O bond of formate to formaldehyde. The reaction proceeds through a surface-bound formyl intermediate.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite surfaces can reduce C1 oxygenates further (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Reduction of formate/CO to formaldehyde-level intermediates on iron-bearing mineral surfaces has been proposed as a key step in prebiotic carbon chain elongation (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997). Fe\u2070 is a thermodynamically strong reductant capable of driving this reduction under hydrothermal conditions (Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formose-type aldol dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay with borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline aqueous pool, pH 10-11, Ca(OH)\u2082 as base, borate stabilizes intermediates"}, "mechanism": "Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol addition. One formaldehyde undergoes umpolung via a Cannizzaro-like enolization to generate a nucleophilic carbanion equivalent, which attacks the second formaldehyde electrophile. Borate minerals complex with the resulting glycolaldehyde diol, stabilizing the product against further Cannizzaro degradation.", "reasoning": "The initial step of the formose reaction generating glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is well-established (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). Borate minerals stabilize sugar products by complexing with cis-diols, preventing sugar degradation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate and orient reactants (Ferris et al., 1996). Glycolaldehyde has been identified as a key interstellar and prebiotic molecule (Hollis et al., 2000)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Slightly alkaline conditions, pH 9-10, borate stabilization of product"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde enolizes under basic conditions, generating a nucleophilic enediol. This carbanion attacks formaldehyde to form a new C\u2013C bond, yielding glyceraldehyde. Borate complexation of the product cis-diol stabilizes glyceraldehyde against retroaldol and epimerization.", "reasoning": "This is the second step of the formose reaction, well-characterized in the literature (Breslow, 1959; Kopetzki & Antonietti, 2011). Borate stabilization of glyceraldehyde is critical for selective sugar synthesis (Ricardo et al., 2004; Kim et al., 2011). This step extends the carbon chain from C2 to C3, setting up the key methylglyoxal intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Direct CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on iron minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite and greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Native iron and sulfide minerals present, serpentinization-derived H\u2082, slightly alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 undergoes stepwise reduction and C\u2013C bond formation on mixed iron oxide-sulfide mineral surfaces. Three CO\u2082 equivalents are reduced and coupled via surface-bound C1 intermediates (formate \u2192 formyl \u2192 CO), forming a C3 skeleton. The terminal carboxylation and keto group formation yields pyruvate. The mechanism parallels the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway in reverse.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on native iron and iron mineral surfaces has been demonstrated experimentally (Cody et al., 2000; Varma et al., 2018). Muchowska et al. (2017) showed that Fe\u2070 can drive the formation of pyruvate and other \u03b1-keto acids from CO\u2082 under mild aqueous conditions. This reaction is a cornerstone of the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082) surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Thermal decarboxylation facilitated by mineral surface and elevated temperature"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes non-oxidative thermal decarboxylation. The \u03b2-keto acid functional group facilitates loss of CO\u2082 through a cyclic transition state, yielding acetaldehyde. Pyrite surface Lewis acid sites coordinate the keto and carboxylate oxygens, lowering the activation barrier for decarboxylation.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids is well-known in organic chemistry and proceeds readily at hydrothermal temperatures (Cooper et al., 2011). Cody et al. (2004) demonstrated pyruvate decarboxylation in hydrothermal systems. Pyrite surfaces catalyze various organic transformations through Lewis acid interactions (Schoonen et al., 1999). This reaction connects the C3 hub pyruvate to the C2 hub acetaldehyde, a critical network link."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Dehydration of glyceraldehyde to methylglyoxal", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly acidic conditions, pH 4-6, UV irradiation, wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes acid-catalyzed elimination of water. The C2 hydroxyl is lost via E1cb mechanism, forming an enol intermediate that tautomerizes to methylglyoxal (2-oxopropanal). TiO\u2082 photocatalysis may generate reactive oxygen species that facilitate the oxidative dehydration. Clay surface acidity promotes the elimination.", "reasoning": "Glyceraldehyde dehydration to methylglyoxal is thermodynamically favorable and occurs under mildly acidic conditions at elevated temperatures (Thornalley, 1996). Methylglyoxal is a well-known product of sugar degradation in the formose reaction (Benner et al., 2012). This transformation is critical for converting the C3 sugar into a C3 dicarbonyl that serves as the direct precursor to lactaldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on mackinawite", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-380K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Selective ketone reduction favored over aldehyde reduction on FeS surface due to steric and electronic selectivity"}, "mechanism": "Methylglyoxal adsorbs on the mackinawite (FeS) surface via the more electrophilic ketone carbonyl. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface, providing surface-bound hydride. Selective transfer of hydride to the ketone C=O yields the secondary alcohol, producing lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) while preserving the aldehyde functionality. The FeS surface provides chemoselective reduction.", "reasoning": "Mackinawite (FeS) is an effective hydrogenation catalyst under hydrothermal conditions (Rickard & Luther, 2007). Selective reduction of ketones over aldehydes on mineral surfaces has been proposed based on differential binding affinities (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998). The selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde is the key step enabling the Strecker route to threonine. FeS-catalyzed reductions of carbonyl compounds under hydrothermal conditions are well-documented (Heinen & Lauwers, 1996)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Acetaldehyde oxidative hydroxylation to methylglyoxal via UV photocatalysis", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), no ozone shield on early Earth, apatite mineral surface"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde and formaldehyde undergo a UV-photocatalyzed cross-aldol condensation on TiO\u2082 surface, followed by oxidation. TiO\u2082 generates electron-hole pairs under UV, producing hydroxyl radicals. Acetaldehyde enolizes and attacks formaldehyde to give 3-hydroxypropanal, which is then oxidized at C1 by TiO\u2082-generated radical species to yield methylglyoxal. Alternatively, acetaldehyde is directly photo-oxidized and then reacts with formaldehyde-derived radicals.", "reasoning": "TiO\u2082 photocatalysis is highly relevant on early Earth where intense UV radiation penetrated the anoxic atmosphere (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). Cross-aldol reactions between C1 and C2 aldehydes are thermodynamically favorable (Kopetzki & Antonietti, 2011). This provides a convergent second route to methylglyoxal from hydrothermal-derived acetaldehyde and formaldehyde, linking hydrothermal outputs to surface photochemistry. Photo-oxidation of organic molecules on TiO\u2082 is well-established (Hoffmann et al., 1995)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mild aqueous conditions, pH 7-9, concentrated evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropanal) reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base) via nucleophilic addition-elimination. The imine is then attacked by cyanide (HCN) in a nucleophilic addition, forming 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (the \u03b1-aminonitrile of threonine). Clay surfaces concentrate reactants and template the reaction through surface adsorption. The hydroxyl group at C3 remains intact throughout.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is the most well-established prebiotic route to amino acids (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957). Formation of \u03b1-aminonitriles from aldehydes, ammonia, and HCN proceeds efficiently under mild aqueous conditions. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes and concentrates these reactions (Ferris, 2005). The use of lactaldehyde as the starting aldehyde specifically yields the threonine \u03b1-aminonitrile (Lerner et al., 1993). This is the most direct prebiotic route to threonine."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous solution, mildly acidic to neutral pH, prolonged heating or UV-assisted hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis. First, water attacks the nitrile carbon to form an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide). Second, the amide undergoes further hydrolysis to yield the free carboxylic acid, releasing ammonia. This yields threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid). The reaction is accelerated by mild heating and acidic conditions.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is a fundamental aqueous reaction and the final step of the Strecker synthesis (Strecker, 1850). Under prebiotic conditions, aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds at moderate rates at pH 4-7 and temperatures above 300K (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). This step converts the Strecker aminonitrile intermediate into the final amino acid product. The reaction requires no special catalysis beyond aqueous solution and mild heating."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-380K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "NH\u2083-rich alkaline vent fluid, high H\u2082 fugacity, mineral surface catalysis"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-keto acid 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base) at the C2 keto position. The imine is then reduced by H\u2082 dissociated on the FeS mineral surface, yielding threonine. The FeS surface acts as a heterogeneous hydrogenation catalyst, facilitating both imine formation and reduction in a one-pot reductive amination.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids is a well-established prebiotic route to amino acids, mimicking extant transamination biochemistry (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 2003). FeS minerals catalyze reductive amination under hydrothermal conditions, as demonstrated for pyruvate \u2192 alanine (Muchowska et al., 2019; Barge et al., 2019). Application to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate yields threonine directly, providing an alternative to the Strecker route. This pathway is thermodynamically favorable under reducing hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Oxidative carboxylation of methylglyoxal to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_001", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, hydrated CO\u2082 (bicarbonate), mineral pool setting"}, "mechanism": "Methylglyoxal undergoes selective hydration at the ketone to form the 2,2-dihydroxy intermediate. UV-driven TiO\u2082 photocatalysis generates reactive carboxylating species from dissolved CO\u2082/bicarbonate. Radical carboxylation at the aldehyde terminus or nucleophilic carboxylation of the hydrated intermediate inserts a CO\u2082-derived carboxyl group, forming 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate. The reaction is analogous to \u03b1-ketoglutarate formation from succinate semialdehyde.", "reasoning": "Photochemical carboxylation reactions are plausible under early Earth UV conditions (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). TiO\u2082-driven CO\u2082 fixation into organic molecules has been demonstrated experimentally (Inoue et al., 1979). The formation of \u03b1-keto acids from shorter-chain aldehydes and CO\u2082 provides a surface-environment pathway to the threonine precursor keto acid, complementing the hydrothermal Strecker route. This is a speculative but thermodynamically feasible connection necessary to complete the reductive amination pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde from CO\u2082 and H\u2082", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084) with native iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal system"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is first reduced to CO on Fe\u2070 surfaces. CO and H\u2082 undergo Fischer-Tropsch-type chain growth on magnetite surfaces via a carbide or formyl insertion mechanism. Sequential hydrogenation and chain extension produces C2 oxygenates. Acetaldehyde is a primary C2 product of FTT synthesis, formed via surface-bound acetyl intermediate hydrogenation.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces in hydrothermal systems has been extensively studied (McCollom et al., 1999; McCollom & Seewald, 2007). Acetaldehyde is among the observed C2 oxygenate products. Foustoukos & Seyfried (2004) demonstrated FTT synthesis of short-chain organics under seafloor hydrothermal conditions. This provides a direct hydrothermal route to acetaldehyde independent of pyruvate decarboxylation."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "HCN hydrolysis and photochemical reduction to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 and MoS\u2082 photocatalysts", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic chemistry conditions, early Earth atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes UV-assisted hydrolysis: HCN + H\u2082O \u2192 formamide (HCONH\u2082) under UV irradiation. Formamide is then photolytically reduced on TiO\u2082/MoS\u2082 surfaces, losing NH\u2083 and gaining H to yield formaldehyde. Alternatively, HCN photohydration proceeds directly to a formaldehyde-imine which hydrolyzes. This cyanosulfidic photochemistry links the HCN pool to the aldehyde pool.", "reasoning": "The photochemical conversion of HCN to formaldehyde and other C1 species via formamide intermediate is part of the Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). UV photolysis of HCN solutions produces formamide and other products (Ferris & Hagan, 1984). TiO\u2082 and MoS\u2082 photocatalysis can drive these transformations under prebiotically relevant UV fluxes. This reaction provides a surface-environment route to formaldehyde complementary to the hydrothermal formate reduction pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Aldol-Tishchenko disproportionation of glycolaldehyde to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with apatite mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline aqueous conditions pH 9-10, evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde enolizes under basic conditions on the montmorillonite surface. The enolate attacks the aldehyde of glycolaldehyde in a cross-aldol addition, forming a C4 diol-aldehyde intermediate (4-hydroxy-2-hydroxymethyl-butanal). The intermediate undergoes retro-aldol/isomerization on the mineral surface to yield lactaldehyde and formaldehyde, driven by the thermodynamic stability of the products. Alternatively, direct cross-aldol gives 2-hydroxybutanal which can isomerize on the clay surface.", "reasoning": "Cross-aldol reactions between C2 aldehydes are fundamental in formose-type chemistry (Breslow, 1959). Montmorillonite clay catalyzes aldol condensations and controls product selectivity through surface templating (Ferris, 2005). The formation of C3 branched and hydroxylated aldehydes from C2 precursors is well-precedented in formose chemistry. This provides a second surface-based route to lactaldehyde directly from two hydrothermal products (glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde), bypassing the methylglyoxal intermediate."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Primary Strecker route via hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde", "description": "The longest and most detailed pathway. CO\u2082 is reduced to formate then formaldehyde in hydrothermal vents. Formaldehyde dimerizes to glycolaldehyde on surface clays, which combines with more formaldehyde to form glyceraldehyde. Glyceraldehyde dehydrates to methylglyoxal, which is selectively reduced to lactaldehyde at hydrothermal vents. Strecker synthesis with NH\u2083 and HCN gives the aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Strecker route via FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde", "description": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis directly produces acetaldehyde from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 in hydrothermal vents. Acetaldehyde and formaldehyde undergo UV-photocatalyzed cross-aldol/oxidation to methylglyoxal on surfaces. Methylglyoxal is reduced to lactaldehyde at vents, followed by Strecker synthesis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_014", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_009", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Strecker route via pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal", "description": "Pyruvate is synthesized directly from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on iron minerals. It undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde at hydrothermal vents. Acetaldehyde and formaldehyde form methylglyoxal photocatalytically, then methylglyoxal is reduced to lactaldehyde. Strecker synthesis completes the threonine pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_009", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Reductive amination route via methylglyoxal carboxylation", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to formaldehyde via formate. Formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal in surface environments. Methylglyoxal is photochemically carboxylated to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate. Reductive amination on FeS surfaces at hydrothermal vents yields threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_013", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Reductive amination via acetaldehyde-derived methylglyoxal carboxylation", "description": "FTT synthesis gives acetaldehyde; hydrothermal formate reduction gives formaldehyde. UV-photocatalytic cross-aldol produces methylglyoxal, which is carboxylated to the \u03b1-keto acid and reductively aminated to threonine at vents.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_014", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_009", "rxn_013", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "HCN-photochemical formaldehyde route to Strecker threonine", "description": "HCN is photochemically hydrolyzed to formaldehyde on TiO\u2082 surfaces. Formaldehyde enters the formose pathway to glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde. Strecker synthesis uses HCN and NH\u2083 to complete threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Cross-aldol lactaldehyde route from glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde", "description": "Hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde (surface). FTT synthesis gives acetaldehyde (hydrothermal). Cross-aldol disproportionation of glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde on clay gives lactaldehyde directly. Strecker synthesis yields threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_014", "rxn_016", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde cross-aldol to lactaldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Pyruvate is formed hydrothermally and decarboxylated to acetaldehyde. Formaldehyde dimerizes to glycolaldehyde. Cross-aldol of glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde on clay yields lactaldehyde. Strecker gives threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_016", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "HCN-derived formaldehyde to reductive amination route", "description": "HCN photochemically produces formaldehyde. Formaldehyde builds up to glyceraldehyde via formose steps, dehydrates to methylglyoxal, which is carboxylated to the \u03b1-keto acid. Reductive amination gives threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_007", "rxn_013", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Mixed FTT-acetaldehyde and pyruvate decarboxylation convergent methylglyoxal route", "description": "Both FTT synthesis (rxn_014) and pyruvate decarboxylation (rxn_005 \u2192 rxn_006) produce acetaldehyde, which converges at the methylglyoxal node via photocatalytic cross-aldol with HCN-derived formaldehyde (rxn_015). Methylglyoxal is reduced to lactaldehyde, and Strecker synthesis gives threonine. This pathway demonstrates maximal convergence of hydrothermal and surface chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_015", "rxn_009", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_009", "mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_008", "mol_010"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Formaldehyde - key C1 building block formed by two routes and consumed by four reactions", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_015", "rxn_016"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Acetaldehyde - C2 hub produced by two distinct hydrothermal routes, consumed by two surface reactions", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_014"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_016"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Methylglyoxal - critical C3 dicarbonyl intermediate where sugar chemistry and aldehyde chemistry converge, feeds both Strecker and reductive amination routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "description": "Lactaldehyde - penultimate Strecker aldehyde formed by two reduction/aldol routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_016"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_016", "description": "Threonine - target molecule formed by two independent final reactions (Strecker hydrolysis and reductive amination)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": []}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 473250.53429603577, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T00:20:10.270646", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: Threonine (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid) is synthesized through a convergent prebiotic network originating from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 in hydrothermal environments, progressing through C1-C3 aldehyde intermediates in surface environments, and culminating in Strecker synthesis and reductive amination routes in surface/biochemical settings. The network leverages formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and pyruvate as hub molecules. Lactaldehyde is the key penultimate aldehyde for the Strecker route, formed via methylglyoxal reduction or cross-aldol chemistry. An alternative route proceeds through the \u03b1-keto acid 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoate and reductive amination. Multiple environmental pathways intersect to provide robust, redundant routes to threonine under early Earth conditions.\n\nMOLECULES (16 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (Carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (Hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (Ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: HCN (Hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: H2O (Water) [starting]\n  - mol_006: CHOO- (Formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CH2O (Formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C2H4O2 (Glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C2H4O (Acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H4O3 (Pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H6O3 (Glyceraldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C3H4O2 (Methylglyoxal) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H6O2 (Lactaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H6N2O (Threonine aminonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C4H6O4 (2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C4H9NO3 (Threonine) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (16 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_006 (CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_006, mol_002 -> mol_007, mol_005 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_007, mol_007 -> mol_008 (Formose-type aldol dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_008, mol_007 -> mol_011 (Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_010 (Direct CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate on iron minerals) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_006: mol_010 -> mol_009, mol_001 (Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_007: mol_011 -> mol_012, mol_005 (Dehydration of glyceraldehyde to methylglyoxal) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_012, mol_002 -> mol_013 (Selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on mackinawite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_009: mol_009, mol_007 -> mol_012 (Acetaldehyde oxidative hydroxylation to methylglyoxal via UV photocatalysis) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_013, mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_014 (Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 threonine aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_014, mol_005 -> mol_016 (Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_015, mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_016 (Reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_013: mol_012, mol_001, mol_005 -> mol_015 (Oxidative carboxylation of methylglyoxal to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_009 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde from CO\u2082 and H\u2082) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_015: mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_007 (HCN hydrolysis and photochemical reduction to formaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016: mol_008, mol_009 -> mol_013, mol_007 (Aldol-Tishchenko disproportionation of glycolaldehyde to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Primary Strecker route via hydrothermal formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde (8 steps)\n  - P2: Strecker route via FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde (7 steps)\n  - P3: Strecker route via pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal (8 steps)\n  - P4: Reductive amination route via methylglyoxal carboxylation (7 steps)\n  - P5: Reductive amination via acetaldehyde-derived methylglyoxal carboxylation (6 steps)\n  - P6: HCN-photochemical formaldehyde route to Strecker threonine (7 steps)\n  - P7: Cross-aldol lactaldehyde route from glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde (7 steps)\n  - P8: Pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde cross-aldol to lactaldehyde Strecker route (8 steps)\n  - P9: HCN-derived formaldehyde to reductive amination route (6 steps)\n  - P10: Mixed FTT-acetaldehyde and pyruvate decarboxylation convergent methylglyoxal route (7 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_007, mol_009, mol_012, mol_008, mol_010\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.