itical weakness is rxn_009: the claim that acetaldehyde and formaldehyde undergo 'oxidative hydroxylation via UV photocatalysis' to give methylglyoxal is chemically unconvincing. An aldol of these two would yield 3-hydroxypropanal, not methylglyoxal; additional oxidation would be needed and the selectivity is unexplained. Environmental bouncing between hydrothermal and surface is also problematic.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace rxn_009 with a well-characterized aldol + oxidation sequence\",\n        \"Consider an alternative route to methylglyoxal from acetaldehyde via pyruvaldehyde pathways\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.40,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.60,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.60,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.64,\n      \"feedback\": \"Pyruvate formation from CO\u2082 on iron minerals is experimentally demonstrated (Muchowska et al. 2019). Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is straightforward. The pathway then suffers from the same rxn_009 weakness as P2. The route from pyruvate to methylglyoxal could be better justified through direct pyruvate reduction and rearrangement rather than going through acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add a direct pyruvate \u2192 methylglyoxal route (pyruvate decarboxylation at the carboxyl end)\",\n        \"Consider pyruvate as a more direct precursor to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate via aldol with formaldehyde\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.