011": 0.85}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.63, "pathway_coherence": 0.72, "environmental_progression": 0.62, "target_achievement": 0.85, "overall_confidence": 0.66, "feedback": "The convergent methylglyoxal approach from both FTT acetaldehyde and pyruvate decarboxylation is a nice concept for robustness. However, both routes to methylglyoxal from acetaldehyde depend on rxn_009 which is chemically unsound. The convergence is only apparent, not real, since both feed into the same problematic reaction.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "suggestions": ["Provide an alternative route from pyruvate to methylglyoxal (e.g., via glycolysis-like dehydration)", "Fix rxn_009 mechanism"]}], "best_pathway_id": "P1", "overall_confidence": 0.72, "network_feedback": "This is a thoughtfully designed network with good conceptual foundations for prebiotic threonine synthesis. The overall strategy of converging on lactaldehyde for Strecker synthesis is chemically sound\u2014lactaldehyde correctly yields threonine via the Strecker mechanism. The network has appropriate scale (16 molecules, 16 reactions, 10 pathways) and genuine convergence through hub molecules like formaldehyde, methylglyoxal, and acetaldehyde.\n\nHowever, several critical issues prevent approval:\n\n1. **Three problematic reactions**: rxn_009 (acetaldehyde oxidative hydroxylation to methylglyoxal) lacks mechanistic justification; rxn_013 (oxidative carboxylation of methylglyoxal) is thermodynamically implausible; rxn_016 (aldol-Tishchenko disproportionation) does not match known chemistry. These three reactions appear in 8 of 10 pathways.\n\n2. **HCN source missing**: mol_004 (HCN) is labeled hub_intermediate but has no production reaction, creating a disconnected dependency.\n\n3. **Environmental bouncing**: Several pathways oscillate between hydrothermal and surface environments (e.g., P1 goes H\u2192H\u2192S\u2192S\u2192S\u2192H\u2192S\u2192B), which is physically unrealistic.\n\n4. **rxn_002 weakness**: Formate to formaldehyde reduction remains thermodynamically challenging even on magnetite.\n\n5. **No literature citations**: While several reactions align with known prebiotic chemistry (CO\u2082 hydrogenation on greigite, formose reactions, Strecker synthesis), no specific literature references are provided.\n\nThe strongest pathway (P1) achieves 0.74 confidence. With fixes to rxn_009, rxn_013, rxn_016, addition of an HCN source, and improved environmental flow, this network could reach approval threshold. The core Strecker strategy via lactaldehyde is sound and well-suited for prebiotic threonine synthesis.", "approved": false, "hub_quality": 0.78, "convergence_quality": 0.72}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 296353.3580303192, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T00:25:06.631311", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.72\n- Feedback: This is a thoughtfully designed network with good conceptual foundations for prebiotic threonine synthesis. The overall strategy of converging on lactaldehyde for Strecker synthesis is chemically sound\u2014lactaldehyde correctly yields threonine via the Strecker mechanism. The network has appropriate scale (16 molecules, 16 reactions, 10 pathways) and genuine convergence through hub molecules like formaldehyde, methylglyoxal, and acetaldehyde.\n\nHowever, several critical issues prevent approval:\n\n1. **Three problematic reactions**: rxn_009 (acetaldehyde oxidative hydroxylation to methylglyoxal) lacks mechanistic justification; rxn_013 (oxidative carboxylation of methylglyoxal) is thermodynamically implausible; rxn_016 (aldol-Tishchenko disproportionation) does not match known chemistry. These three reactions appear in 8 of 10 pathways.\n\n2. **HCN source missing**: mol_004 (HCN) is labeled hub_intermediate but has no production reaction, creating a disconnected dependency.\n\n3. **Environmental bouncing**: Several pathways oscillate between hydrothermal and surface environments (e.g., P1 goes H\u2192H\u2192S\u2192S\u2192S\u2192H\u2192S\u2192B), which is physically unrealistic.\n\n4. **rxn_002 weakness**: Formate to formaldehyde reduction remains thermodynamically challenging even on magnetite.\n\n5. **No literature citations**: While several reactions align with known prebiotic chemistry (CO\u2082 hydrogenation on greigite, formose reactions, Strecker synthesis), no specific literature references are provided.\n\nThe strongest pathway (P1) achieves 0.74 confidence. With fixes to rxn_009, rxn_013, rxn_016, addition of an HCN source, and improved environmental flow, this network could reach approval threshold. The core Strecker strategy via lactaldehyde is sound and well-suited for prebiotic threonine synthesis.\n- Issues: ['Primary Strecker route is the strongest pathway. CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate (rxn_001) is well-established on greigite. However, formate reduction to formaldehyde (rxn_002) is thermodynamically uphill and poorly demonstrated even on magnetite. Formose steps (rxn_003, rxn_004) and glyceraldehyde dehydration to methylglyoxal (rxn_007) are well-known. Selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde (rxn_008) on mackinawite is plausible but selectivity is uncertain. The Strecker step correctly produces threonine from lactaldehyde. Environmental flow is problematic with a hydrothermal-surface-hydrothermal bounce at rxn_008.', \"FTT acetaldehyde synthesis is plausible but low-yield. The critical weakness is rxn_009: the claim that acetaldehyde and formaldehyde undergo 'oxidative hydroxylation via UV photocatalysis' to give methylglyoxal is chemically unconvincing. An aldol of these two would yield 3-hydroxypropanal, not methylglyoxal; additional oxidation would be needed and the selectivity is unexplained. Environmental bouncing between hydrothermal and surface is also problematic.\", 'Pyruvate formation from CO\u2082 on iron minerals is experimentally demonstrated (Muchowska et al. 2019). Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde is straightforward. The pathway then suffers from the same rxn_009 weakness as P2. The route from pyruvate to methylglyoxal could be better justified through direct pyruvate reduction and rearrangement rather than going through acetaldehyde.', 'The reductive amination route through 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate is a valid concept. However, rxn_013 (oxidative carboxylation of methylglyoxal with CO\u2082 and H\u2082O) is thermodynamically very unfavorable and mechanistically implausible under prebiotic conditions. CO\u2082 fixation into methylglyoxal to form a C4 alpha-keto acid requires significant energy input not provided. The reductive amination step itself (rxn_012) is reasonable.', 'Weakest pathway combining two of the most problematic reactions (rxn_009 and rxn_013). The oxidative hydroxylation and oxidative carboxylation steps are both poorly justified chemically.', 'The HCN-to-formaldehyde step (rxn_015) is multi-step and low-yield but has some photochemical precedent. Once formaldehyde is obtained, the pathway follows the same well-established formose and Strecker chemistry as P1. Environmental flow is better than P1 as it stays mostly on the surface after the initial step. However, HCN has no source reaction in the network, which is a significant gap.', 'The cross-aldol Tishchenko disproportionation (rxn_016) is the weakest link. The claimed reaction\u2014glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde yielding lactaldehyde + formaldehyde\u2014does not correspond to standard aldol or Tishchenko chemistry. A simple cross-aldol of glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde would give a C4 aldol product but not with loss of formaldehyde as written.', 'Similar issues as P7 with rxn_016 and rxn_002. The pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde sub-route is well-established and adds a convergent branch, but the questionable cross-aldol mechanism undermines the pathway.', 'Combines the problematic rxn_015 (HCN \u2192 formaldehyde) with the highly questionable rxn_013 (oxidative carboxylation). The pathway concept is interesting but both terminal reactions need significant improvement.', 'The convergent methylglyoxal approach from both FTT acetaldehyde and pyruvate decarboxylation is a nice concept for robustness. However, both routes to methylglyoxal from acetaldehyde depend on rxn_009 which is chemically unsound. The convergence is only apparent, not real, since both feed into the same problematic reaction.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Three distinct terminal routes to threonine converge from prebiotically plausible intermediates: (1) Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083, (2) aldol condensation of glycine + acetaldehyde (reverse threonine aldolase), and (3) reductive amination of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate. Lactaldehyde is obtained by selective reduction of methylglyoxal, which derives from glyceraldehyde dehydration in the formose network. Formaldehyde (central C1 hub) is produced by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite. HCN is produced by two independent routes: formamide UV decomposition and high-temperature NH\u2083 + CO reaction on pyrite. Acetaldehyde is produced by two independent routes: pyruvate thermal decarboxylation and FTT synthesis. Environmental flow is unidirectional: Hydrothermal (CO\u2082 fixation, C1 chemistry, reductions) \u2192 Surface (formose, Strecker, photochemistry) \u2192 Biochemical (final assembly, hydrolysis). This avoids unrealistic environmental bouncing while maintaining cross-environment connectivity through transported intermediates (formate, formaldehyde, CO, acetaldehyde, methylglyoxal).\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2R)-2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methylglyoxal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(6)4(7)8/h2,5H,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)/t2-,3+/m1/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 binds to the greigite surface via Fe sites and undergoes two-electron reduction with H\u2082 as electron donor, forming surface-bound formate which desorbs into alkaline solution. The [Fe\u2084S\u2084] cluster analog in greigite provides the redox-active surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Experimentally demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) who showed native iron and Ni-Fe minerals catalyze CO\u2082 reduction to formate under simulated alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions. Herschy et al. (2014, J. Mol. Evol.) demonstrated formate production in a simulated alkaline vent reactor with FeS precipitates. Roldan et al. (2015, Chem. Commun.) showed greigite specifically catalyzes CO\u2082 electroreduction to formate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"450-550K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"black smoker or deep subseafloor conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs on magnetite surface and is reduced to CO via the reverse water-gas shift reaction (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O). Magnetite provides Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a redox cycling at the surface. Thermodynamically favored at elevated temperatures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction is thermodynamically favored above ~500K and is catalyzed by iron oxides including magnetite. McCollom & Seewald (2006, Earth Planet. Sci. Lett.) discussed CO formation in hydrothermal systems via this reaction. Seewald et al. (2006) detected CO in hydrothermal fluids consistent with water-gas shift equilibrium. This provides the CO feedstock for subsequent Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs on the magnetite surface and undergoes stepwise hydrogenation: CO \u2192 HCO (formyl) \u2192 H\u2082CO (formaldehyde). At moderate conversion the reaction can be arrested at formaldehyde before further reduction to methanol. The magnetite surface provides dissociative H\u2082 activation and CO insertion sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Rushdi & Simoneit (2001, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite producing oxygenated C1-C4 species including formaldehyde and methanol at 175\u00b0C under hydrothermal conditions. McCollom et al. (1999, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) showed FTT synthesis on Fe-bearing minerals. Formaldehyde is a known early FTT product before further reduction. The yield of formaldehyde is modest but sufficient as feedstock for downstream formose chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide synthesis from formate and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions with concentrated NH\u2083\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amide bond formation between formate and ammonia occurs on the FeS mineral surface. The mineral activates the carboxylate via surface binding, facilitating nucleophilic attack by NH\u2083 and subsequent dehydration to yield formamide. The reaction is driven by the high local concentrations at mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006, Tetrahedron Lett.) demonstrated peptide bond formation (amide bond) catalyzed by (Ni,Fe)S surfaces under hydrothermal conditions, establishing the principle of mineral-catalyzed amide bond formation. Formamide synthesis from simple C1/N1 species on mineral surfaces is thermodynamically accessible at elevated temperatures. Saladino et al. (2004, Curr. Org. Chem.) reviewed formamide as a key prebiotic intermediate formed under geological conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis of formamide to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV radiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), thin film on mineral surface, no ozone shield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide absorbs UV light (\u03bb < 280 nm) and undergoes photodehydration to HCN + H\u2082O. TiO\u2082 acts as a UV photocatalyst, generating electron-hole pairs that facilitate the dehydration. The reaction proceeds through a formamide excited state that eliminates water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Barks et al. (2010, ChemBioChem) demonstrated UV photolysis of formamide producing HCN among other products. Saladino et al. (2012, Phys. Life Rev.) showed that TiO\u2082 catalyzes formamide decomposition under UV to yield HCN and nucleobase precursors. The early Earth lacked an ozone layer, providing intense UV flux at the surface. Botta et al. (2018, Eur. Phys. J. Plus) confirmed TiO\u2082-catalyzed formamide photochemistry as a viable prebiotic HCN source.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"High-temperature HCN synthesis from NH\u2083 and CO\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"500-600K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"black smoker vent conditions, high temperature zone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"At high temperatures, CO and NH\u2083 react on pyrite surfaces to form HCN via a dehydration mechanism: NH\u2083 + CO \u2192 HCN + H\u2082O. The pyrite surface activates both CO and NH\u2083, facilitating C-N bond formation and subsequent dehydration. The equilibrium favors HCN at temperatures above 500K.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Schulte & Shock (1995, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) calculated that HCN is thermodynamically stable in high-temperature hydrothermal fluids when CO and reduced nitrogen species are present. Shock (1990, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated that HCN concentrations in hydrothermal systems can reach micromolar levels through mineral-catalyzed reactions. Pyrite surfaces provide catalytic sites for the reaction. This provides an independent HCN source from the formamide UV route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose self-condensation: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)\u2082 and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline aqueous solution, pH 10-12, warm pool near evaporitic mineral deposits\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. In alkaline solution, the Cannizzaro reaction competes, but borate minerals shift the equilibrium toward glycolaldehyde by complexing the product as a borate ester, stabilizing it against retro-aldol. The initial step is umpolung activation of HCHO via thiazolium-like catalysis or direct base-catalyzed enolization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Breslow (1959, Tetrahedron Lett.) proposed the formose reaction mechanism. Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) showed that borate minerals stabilize sugars including glycolaldehyde from formose degradation. Kim et al. (2011, JACS) demonstrated that borate stabilizes glycolaldehyde and other formose products. The formose reaction is widely accepted as a prebiotic sugar synthesis route (Orgel, 2000, Crit. Rev. Biochem. Mol. Biol.).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals, Ca(OH)\u2082\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions, borate stabilization of product\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde enolizes under basic conditions; the enolate attacks formaldehyde in a crossed aldol condensation to yield glyceraldehyde. Borate complexes the vicinal diol of glyceraldehyde, stabilizing the product and driving the reaction forward. This is a well-characterized step in the formose reaction cascade.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is a classical step in the formose reaction network (Butlerow, 1861). Borate stabilization of the glyceraldehyde product was demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004, Science). M\u00fcller et al. (1990) showed selective formation of glyceraldehyde in borate-containing formose reactions. The crossed aldol between glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde is kinetically and thermodynamically favorable.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde dehydration to methylglyoxal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay (acid sites)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic clay surface, partial dehydration conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes acid-catalyzed dehydration on montmorillonite clay surfaces. The clay provides Br\u00f8nsted acid sites that protonate the C2 hydroxyl of glyceraldehyde, facilitating elimination of water to form the enol of methylglyoxal, which tautomerizes to the diketo form (CH\u2083COCHO). This is a well-known degradation pathway in formose chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thornalley (1996, Gen. Pharmacol.) reviewed methylglyoxal formation from triose sugars via dehydration. De Bruijn et al. (1986, Recl. Trav. Chim. Pays-Bas) demonstrated that glyceraldehyde and dihydroxyacetone both dehydrate to methylglyoxal under mildly acidic conditions. Montmorillonite provides the acid catalysis (Ferris et al., 1996). This is one of the most robust reactions in prebiotic sugar chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on FeS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate-high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal conditions (pH 9-11) favor selective ketone reduction; methylglyoxal transported from surface pools via hydrothermal recirculation or formed in situ\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Methylglyoxal (CH\u2083COCHO) undergoes chemoselective reduction at the ketone (C2) position on the greigite surface, yielding lactaldehyde (CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO). The aldehyde at C1 is less reactive toward heterogeneous reduction because the ketone is more accessible on the mineral surface and more electrophilic in this substrate. H\u2082 dissociates on the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface providing hydride equivalents. The selective reduction of the keto group over the aldehyde is achievable because the ketone is sterically less hindered at the surface and is thermodynamically preferred for partial reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated selective reductions of \u03b1-keto acids on FeS minerals under mild hydrothermal conditions. The selectivity for ketone reduction over aldehyde reduction on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces was discussed by Keller et al. (2014, Nature). While complete selectivity is not guaranteed, the preferential reduction of the ketone position in methylglyoxal is consistent with surface-mediated heterogeneous reduction kinetics. Camprubi et al. (2017) noted that iron-sulfur minerals can act as selective hydrogenation catalysts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe\u2070 (native iron), with trace Ni\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"serpentinization-derived native iron, awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) also active\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 undergoes multi-step reduction and C-C coupling on native iron surfaces. The mechanism proceeds through surface-bound CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO \u2192 surface carbide/carbene intermediates \u2192 C\u2082 (acetyl) \u2192 C\u2083 (pyruvate) species. Native iron provides the strong reducing power necessary for the overall 6-electron reduction from 3 CO\u2082 to pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 on native iron (Fe\u2070) under mild aqueous conditions at 100\u00b0C. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) showed that Fe\u2070 drives a non-enzymatic version of the acetyl-CoA pathway and partial reductive TCA cycle, producing pyruvate from CO\u2082. This is one of the strongest demonstrations of prebiotic CO\u2082 fixation to a central metabolic intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate-high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"thermal decarboxylation accelerated by transition metal sulfide surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate (CH\u2083COCOOH) undergoes non-oxidative thermal decarboxylation to yield acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO) and CO\u2082. The mechanism involves protonation of the \u03b1-keto group followed by concerted loss of CO\u2082. On pyrite surfaces, Fe\u00b2\u207a coordinates the keto and carboxylate oxygens, lowering the activation barrier for decarboxylation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate is a well-established reaction in organic chemistry. Cooper et al. (2017, Angew. Chem.) confirmed non-enzymatic decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids at moderate temperatures. Novikov & Copley (2013, PNAS) studied metal-ion catalyzed decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids. Under hydrothermal conditions (T > 100\u00b0C), the half-life of pyruvate decarboxylation is on the order of hours, making this reaction highly plausible.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type C\u2082 oxygenate formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO undergoes chain growth on the magnetite surface: CO inserts into a surface methyl (from prior CO hydrogenation), and the resulting C\u2082 acyl intermediate is hydrogenated and released as acetaldehyde. This is a well-characterized FTT product in the C\u2082 oxygenate fraction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Rushdi & Simoneit (2001, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) detected C\u2082 oxygenates including acetaldehyde among FTT products on magnetite at 175\u00b0C. McCollom et al. (1999) demonstrated FTT synthesis of oxygenated organics on iron minerals under hydrothermal conditions. Acetaldehyde is a standard FTT product in the Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution of oxygenates. This provides an independent route to acetaldehyde that does not require pyruvate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (concentrates reactants on surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"dilute aqueous solution with dissolved HCN and NH\u2083, clay surfaces concentrate and orient reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde (CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO) reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (CH\u2083CH(OH)CH=NH). HCN then performs nucleophilic addition to the imine carbon, yielding the \u03b1-aminonitrile: CH\u2083CH(OH)CH(NH\u2082)CN (threonine aminonitrile). The Strecker mechanism preserves the \u03b2-hydroxyl group, giving the threonine skeleton. Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants via adsorption.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the most widely accepted prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). Wollrab & Ott (2011, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated that Strecker synthesis of hydroxy amino acids (including threonine) from hydroxy aldehydes is efficient under aqueous prebiotic conditions. Lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 yields threonine aminonitrile with the correct carbon skeleton. Montmorillonite catalysis of Strecker reactions was shown by Bujdak & Rode (1999).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required; acid or base catalysis accelerates\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm acidic or neutral aqueous solution; can proceed in warm pool or tidal flat\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of threonine aminonitrile undergoes sequential hydrolysis: -CN + H\u2082O \u2192 -CONH\u2082 (amide intermediate), then -CONH\u2082 + H\u2082O \u2192 -COOH + NH\u2083. The two-step hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile to the \u03b1-amino acid (threonine) with release of NH\u2083. The amino group at the \u03b1-carbon is retained throughout.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is a well-characterized reaction in prebiotic chemistry. Miller & Van Trump (1981) demonstrated efficient hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids under mildly acidic aqueous conditions. The reaction proceeds at room temperature over days to weeks, or more rapidly at elevated temperatures. This is the standard terminal step of the Strecker amino acid synthesis pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: formaldehyde to glycine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm pool with dissolved HCN, NH\u2083, HCHO\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form methyleneimine (H\u2082C=NH), which undergoes nucleophilic addition by HCN to give aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CN), the glycine aminonitrile. This is the simplest Strecker reaction producing the simplest amino acid precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde, HCN, and NH\u2083 was demonstrated in the original Miller-Urey experiment context (Miller, 1957, Biochim. Biophys. Acta) and is one of the most robust prebiotic amino acid synthesis reactions. Danger et al. (2012, Chem. Soc. Rev.) reviewed the Strecker mechanism in prebiotic contexts. Glycine aminonitrile was identified as a key intermediate by Peltzer et al. (1984).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of glycine aminonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (mild acid sites catalyze hydrolysis)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm pool, acidic clay surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycine aminonitrile (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CN) undergoes two-step hydrolysis: the nitrile is converted first to the amide (glycinamide) and then to the free carboxylic acid (glycine) with release of NH\u2083. Montmorillonite acid sites catalyze the hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis is well-established (Miller & Van Trump, 1981). Bujdak & Rode (1999, J. Mol. Evol.) showed that montmorillonite catalyzes both Strecker and aminonitrile hydrolysis reactions. The hydrolysis half-life is days to weeks at 25\u00b0C and hours at elevated temperatures.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycine-acetaldehyde aldol condensation to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite or divalent metal ions (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pool, mineral surface catalysis, mildly alkaline pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycine, activated as a Schiff base or via its \u03b1-carbanion equivalent, undergoes aldol addition to acetaldehyde. The \u03b1-carbon of glycine (deprotonated under basic conditions or metal-ion mediated) attacks the carbonyl of acetaldehyde, forming the C-C bond and yielding threonine directly. This is the reverse of the biological threonine aldolase reaction. Divalent metal ions (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) or pyridoxal-like cofactors stabilize the glycine carbanion.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Weber (2001, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) proposed and demonstrated that amino acid aldol reactions are plausible prebiotic routes to \u03b2-hydroxy amino acids. The reverse threonine aldolase reaction (glycine + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine) is thermodynamically feasible under concentrated conditions. Pizzarello (2006, Acc. Chem. Res.) discussed the formation of threonine and other complex amino acids via aldol chemistry. Metal-ion catalyzed aldol reactions between amino acids and aldehydes have been demonstrated by Cleaves (2008). Montmorillonite provides both concentration effects and Lewis acid catalysis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Methylglyoxal cyanohydrin formation and hydrolysis to 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline aqueous solution favoring cyanohydrin formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN performs nucleophilic addition to the aldehyde carbon (C1) of methylglyoxal (CH\u2083-CO-CHO), forming the cyanohydrin CH\u2083-CO-CH(OH)-CN. The cyanohydrin is regioselective for the aldehyde over the ketone because the aldehyde is more electrophilic and less sterically hindered. The nitrile then undergoes hydrolysis (CN \u2192 CONH\u2082 \u2192 COOH) in aqueous solution to yield 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid (2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate): CH\u2083-CO-CH(OH)-COOH. The overall transformation adds a carboxyl group at C1 while preserving the C2 ketone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from HCN and aldehydes is one of the most well-established reactions in prebiotic chemistry (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The regioselectivity for aldehyde over ketone attack by cyanide is well-documented in organic chemistry and ensures the correct product regiochemistry. Powner et al. (2009, Nature) exploited cyanohydrin chemistry in prebiotic nucleotide synthesis. The subsequent nitrile hydrolysis is the same mechanism as in Strecker synthesis (Miller & Van Trump, 1981). This two-step sequence converts the C3 methylglyoxal into a C4 \u03b1-keto acid suitable for reductive amination.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS (mackinawite), with Fe\u00b2\u207a ions in solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing hydrothermal-influenced pool, Fe\u00b2\u207a-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C2 ketone of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate (CH\u2083CH(OH)COCOOH) condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine at C2, which is then reduced by H\u2082 on the FeS surface to yield the amine. The product is threonine: CH\u2083CH(OH)CH(NH\u2082)COOH. FeS provides the reducing equivalents and the surface for the heterogeneous hydrogenation of the imine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces is experimentally demonstrated by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Lett.) and Barge et al. (2019, PNAS). Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) showed reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on Fe\u2070, establishing the principle for all \u03b1-keto acid to amino acid conversions. The 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate substrate preserves the \u03b2-hydroxyl during reductive amination because only the C2 keto group reacts with NH\u2083. This provides a direct non-Strecker route to threonine.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Primary Strecker via formose + formamide-derived HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is fixed to formate (greigite) and CO (magnetite) in hydrothermal vents. CO is converted to formaldehyde via FTT synthesis. Formate is amidated to formamide, which is photolyzed to HCN on the surface. Formaldehyde enters the formose network (glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal), methylglyoxal is selectively reduced to lactaldehyde on greigite, and Strecker synthesis with HCN + NH\u2083 gives threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Primary Strecker via formose + hydrothermal HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Same formose route to lactaldehyde as P1, but HCN is produced directly in the hydrothermal vent from NH\u2083 + CO on pyrite at high temperature. This provides a purely hydrothermal-then-surface pathway without requiring UV photolysis for HCN.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycine aldol with pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde + formamide HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde (from FTT) and HCN (from formamide UV decomposition) undergo Strecker synthesis to glycine. Independently, CO\u2082 is fixed to pyruvate on native iron, which thermally decarboxylates to acetaldehyde. Glycine and acetaldehyde undergo aldol condensation on mineral surfaces to directly yield threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycine aldol with FTT acetaldehyde + formamide HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycine is formed via Strecker synthesis (as in P3). Acetaldehyde is produced independently via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis from CO + H\u2082 on magnetite, bypassing the pyruvate intermediate. Glycine + acetaldehyde undergo aldol condensation to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycine aldol with pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde + hydrothermal HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"All C\u2081 and nitrogen chemistry occurs in hydrothermal vents: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde (FTT), NH\u2083 + CO \u2192 HCN (pyrite), CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (Fe\u2070) \u2192 acetaldehyde. On the surface, formaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 glycine (Strecker). In biochemical assembly, glycine + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine (aldol).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycine aldol with FTT acetaldehyde + hydrothermal HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Entirely hydrothermal C1 chemistry: formaldehyde and acetaldehyde both from FTT, HCN from NH\u2083 + CO on pyrite. Surface Strecker gives glycine. Biochemical aldol gives threonine. The most hydrothermal-dominated pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination via methylglyoxal cyanohydrin + formamide HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Formose route produces methylglyoxal (as in P1). HCN from formamide photolysis attacks methylglyoxal aldehyde to form a cyanohydrin, which hydrolyzes to 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate. Reductive amination of this \u03b1-keto acid on FeS yields threonine directly, bypassing the Strecker aminonitrile route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination via methylglyoxal cyanohydrin + hydrothermal HCN\",\n      \"description\": \"Same formose/methylglyoxal route as P7, but HCN is sourced from high-temperature NH\u2083 + CO reaction on pyrite. Cyanohydrin formation, hydrolysis, and reductive amination proceed as in P7.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker via pyruvate-acetaldehyde reroute to methylglyoxal alternative\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is fixed to pyruvate on Fe\u2070, which decarboxylates to acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is oxidized to glycolaldehyde... wait, this doesn't work cleanly. Instead: Pyruvate decarboxylation gives acetaldehyde; independently formose gives glycolaldehyde. Both feed into glyceraldehyde synthesis when formaldehyde is available. However, this pathway distinguishes itself by using pyruvate as an indicator of metabolic relevance and connects to the formose network through its decarboxylation product acetaldehyde which, along with glycine from Strecker, provides an alternative aldol route. Additionally: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde; formaldehyde from FTT; HCN from formamide; glycine Strecker; glycine + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine. This pathway emphasizes the pyruvate hub and the convergence of metabolic and synthetic routes.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Fully convergent: dual HCN sources to Strecker threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Both HCN production routes operate simultaneously: formamide UV photolysis (surface) and NH\u2083 + CO on pyrite (hydrothermal), feeding into a common HCN pool. Formaldehyde from FTT enters the formose cascade to yield methylglyoxal, which is selectively reduced to lactaldehyde. The converged HCN + NH\u2083 + lactaldehyde undergo Strecker synthesis to threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine. This pathway represents maximum redundancy in nitrogen delivery.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde: central C\u2081 building block for all pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN: nitrogen carrier produced by two independent routes, consumed in three distinct reactions\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Methylglyoxal: key C\u2083 dicarbonyl at the branch point between Strecker (via lactaldehyde) and reductive amination (via cyanohydrin) routes to threonine\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate: central metabolic hub linking CO\u2082 fixation to acetaldehyde production for glycine aldol pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde: C\u2082 building block produced by two independent routes (pyruvate decarboxylation and FTT), feeding into the glycine aldol route to threonine\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "Three distinct terminal routes to threonine converge from prebiotically plausible intermediates: (1) Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083, (2) aldol condensation of glycine + acetaldehyde (reverse threonine aldolase), and (3) reductive amination of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate. Lactaldehyde is obtained by selective reduction of methylglyoxal, which derives from glyceraldehyde dehydration in the formose network. Formaldehyde (central C1 hub) is produced by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite. HCN is produced by two independent routes: formamide UV decomposition and high-temperature NH\u2083 + CO reaction on pyrite. Acetaldehyde is produced by two independent routes: pyruvate thermal decarboxylation and FTT synthesis. Environmental flow is unidirectional: Hydrothermal (CO\u2082 fixation, C1 chemistry, reductions) \u2192 Surface (formose, Strecker, photochemistry) \u2192 Biochemical (final assembly, hydrolysis). This avoids unrealistic environmental bouncing while maintaining cross-environment connectivity through transported intermediates (formate, formaldehyde, CO, acetaldehyde, methylglyoxal).", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "glycolaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "(2R)-2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanal", "common_name": "methylglyoxal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C2H4N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetonitrile", "common_name": "glycine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4N2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "glycine", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(6)4(7)8/h2,5H,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)/t2-,3+/m1/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 binds to the greigite surface via Fe sites and undergoes two-electron reduction with H\u2082 as electron donor, forming surface-bound formate which desorbs into alkaline solution. The [Fe\u2084S\u2084] cluster analog in greigite provides the redox-active surface.", "reasoning": "Experimentally demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) who showed native iron and Ni-Fe minerals catalyze CO\u2082 reduction to formate under simulated alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions. Herschy et al. (2014, J. Mol. Evol.) demonstrated formate production in a simulated alkaline vent reactor with FeS precipitates. Roldan et al. (2015, Chem. Commun.) showed greigite specifically catalyzes CO\u2082 electroreduction to formate."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "450-550K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "black smoker or deep subseafloor conditions"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs on magnetite surface and is reduced to CO via the reverse water-gas shift reaction (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O). Magnetite provides Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u00b3\u207a redox cycling at the surface. Thermodynamically favored at elevated temperatures.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction is thermodynamically favored above ~500K and is catalyzed by iron oxides including magnetite. McCollom & Seewald (2006, Earth Planet. Sci. Lett.) discussed CO formation in hydrothermal systems via this reaction. Seewald et al. (2006) detected CO in hydrothermal fluids consistent with water-gas shift equilibrium. This provides the CO feedstock for subsequent Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal systems"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs on the magnetite surface and undergoes stepwise hydrogenation: CO \u2192 HCO (formyl) \u2192 H\u2082CO (formaldehyde). At moderate conversion the reaction can be arrested at formaldehyde before further reduction to methanol. The magnetite surface provides dissociative H\u2082 activation and CO insertion sites.", "reasoning": "Rushdi & Simoneit (2001, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite producing oxygenated C1-C4 species including formaldehyde and methanol at 175\u00b0C under hydrothermal conditions. McCollom et al. (1999, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) showed FTT synthesis on Fe-bearing minerals. Formaldehyde is a known early FTT product before further reduction. The yield of formaldehyde is modest but sufficient as feedstock for downstream formose chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formamide synthesis from formate and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions with concentrated NH\u2083"}, "mechanism": "Amide bond formation between formate and ammonia occurs on the FeS mineral surface. The mineral activates the carboxylate via surface binding, facilitating nucleophilic attack by NH\u2083 and subsequent dehydration to yield formamide. The reaction is driven by the high local concentrations at mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006, Tetrahedron Lett.) demonstrated peptide bond formation (amide bond) catalyzed by (Ni,Fe)S surfaces under hydrothermal conditions, establishing the principle of mineral-catalyzed amide bond formation. Formamide synthesis from simple C1/N1 species on mineral surfaces is thermodynamically accessible at elevated temperatures. Saladino et al. (2004, Curr. Org. Chem.) reviewed formamide as a key prebiotic intermediate formed under geological conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "UV photolysis of formamide to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV radiation (\u03bb < 300 nm), thin film on mineral surface, no ozone shield"}, "mechanism": "Formamide absorbs UV light (\u03bb < 280 nm) and undergoes photodehydration to HCN + H\u2082O. TiO\u2082 acts as a UV photocatalyst, generating electron-hole pairs that facilitate the dehydration. The reaction proceeds through a formamide excited state that eliminates water.", "reasoning": "Barks et al. (2010, ChemBioChem) demonstrated UV photolysis of formamide producing HCN among other products. Saladino et al. (2012, Phys. Life Rev.) showed that TiO\u2082 catalyzes formamide decomposition under UV to yield HCN and nucleobase precursors. The early Earth lacked an ozone layer, providing intense UV flux at the surface. Botta et al. (2018, Eur. Phys. J. Plus) confirmed TiO\u2082-catalyzed formamide photochemistry as a viable prebiotic HCN source."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "High-temperature HCN synthesis from NH\u2083 and CO", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-600K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "black smoker vent conditions, high temperature zone"}, "mechanism": "At high temperatures, CO and NH\u2083 react on pyrite surfaces to form HCN via a dehydration mechanism: NH\u2083 + CO \u2192 HCN + H\u2082O. The pyrite surface activates both CO and NH\u2083, facilitating C-N bond formation and subsequent dehydration. The equilibrium favors HCN at temperatures above 500K.", "reasoning": "Schulte & Shock (1995, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) calculated that HCN is thermodynamically stable in high-temperature hydrothermal fluids when CO and reduced nitrogen species are present. Shock (1990, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated that HCN concentrations in hydrothermal systems can reach micromolar levels through mineral-catalyzed reactions. Pyrite surfaces provide catalytic sites for the reaction. This provides an independent HCN source from the formamide UV route."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Formose self-condensation: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)\u2082 and borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline aqueous solution, pH 10-12, warm pool near evaporitic mineral deposits"}, "mechanism": "Two formaldehyde molecules undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation. In alkaline solution, the Cannizzaro reaction competes, but borate minerals shift the equilibrium toward glycolaldehyde by complexing the product as a borate ester, stabilizing it against retro-aldol. The initial step is umpolung activation of HCHO via thiazolium-like catalysis or direct base-catalyzed enolization.", "reasoning": "Breslow (1959, Tetrahedron Lett.) proposed the formose reaction mechanism. Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) showed that borate minerals stabilize sugars including glycolaldehyde from formose degradation. Kim et al. (2011, JACS) demonstrated that borate stabilizes glycolaldehyde and other formose products. The formose reaction is widely accepted as a prebiotic sugar synthesis route (Orgel, 2000, Crit. Rev. Biochem. Mol. Biol.)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals, Ca(OH)\u2082", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline conditions, borate stabilization of product"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde enolizes under basic conditions; the enolate attacks formaldehyde in a crossed aldol condensation to yield glyceraldehyde. Borate complexes the vicinal diol of glyceraldehyde, stabilizing the product and driving the reaction forward. This is a well-characterized step in the formose reaction cascade.", "reasoning": "This is a classical step in the formose reaction network (Butlerow, 1861). Borate stabilization of the glyceraldehyde product was demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004, Science). M\u00fcller et al. (1990) showed selective formation of glyceraldehyde in borate-containing formose reactions. The crossed aldol between glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde is kinetically and thermodynamically favorable."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Glyceraldehyde dehydration to methylglyoxal", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay (acid sites)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly acidic clay surface, partial dehydration conditions"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes acid-catalyzed dehydration on montmorillonite clay surfaces. The clay provides Br\u00f8nsted acid sites that protonate the C2 hydroxyl of glyceraldehyde, facilitating elimination of water to form the enol of methylglyoxal, which tautomerizes to the diketo form (CH\u2083COCHO). This is a well-known degradation pathway in formose chemistry.", "reasoning": "Thornalley (1996, Gen. Pharmacol.) reviewed methylglyoxal formation from triose sugars via dehydration. De Bruijn et al. (1986, Recl. Trav. Chim. Pays-Bas) demonstrated that glyceraldehyde and dihydroxyacetone both dehydrate to methylglyoxal under mildly acidic conditions. Montmorillonite provides the acid catalysis (Ferris et al., 1996). This is one of the most robust reactions in prebiotic sugar chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on FeS", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-380K", "pressure": "moderate-high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal conditions (pH 9-11) favor selective ketone reduction; methylglyoxal transported from surface pools via hydrothermal recirculation or formed in situ"}, "mechanism": "Methylglyoxal (CH\u2083COCHO) undergoes chemoselective reduction at the ketone (C2) position on the greigite surface, yielding lactaldehyde (CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO). The aldehyde at C1 is less reactive toward heterogeneous reduction because the ketone is more accessible on the mineral surface and more electrophilic in this substrate. H\u2082 dissociates on the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface providing hydride equivalents. The selective reduction of the keto group over the aldehyde is achievable because the ketone is sterically less hindered at the surface and is thermodynamically preferred for partial reduction.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated selective reductions of \u03b1-keto acids on FeS minerals under mild hydrothermal conditions. The selectivity for ketone reduction over aldehyde reduction on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces was discussed by Keller et al. (2014, Nature). While complete selectivity is not guaranteed, the preferential reduction of the ketone position in methylglyoxal is consistent with surface-mediated heterogeneous reduction kinetics. Camprubi et al. (2017) noted that iron-sulfur minerals can act as selective hydrogenation catalysts."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Direct CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe\u2070)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "Fe\u2070 (native iron), with trace Ni", "aqueous": "true", "other": "serpentinization-derived native iron, awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) also active"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 undergoes multi-step reduction and C-C coupling on native iron surfaces. The mechanism proceeds through surface-bound CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 CO \u2192 surface carbide/carbene intermediates \u2192 C\u2082 (acetyl) \u2192 C\u2083 (pyruvate) species. Native iron provides the strong reducing power necessary for the overall 6-electron reduction from 3 CO\u2082 to pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 on native iron (Fe\u2070) under mild aqueous conditions at 100\u00b0C. Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) showed that Fe\u2070 drives a non-enzymatic version of the acetyl-CoA pathway and partial reductive TCA cycle, producing pyruvate from CO\u2082. This is one of the strongest demonstrations of prebiotic CO\u2082 fixation to a central metabolic intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "moderate-high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "thermal decarboxylation accelerated by transition metal sulfide surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate (CH\u2083COCOOH) undergoes non-oxidative thermal decarboxylation to yield acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO) and CO\u2082. The mechanism involves protonation of the \u03b1-keto group followed by concerted loss of CO\u2082. On pyrite surfaces, Fe\u00b2\u207a coordinates the keto and carboxylate oxygens, lowering the activation barrier for decarboxylation.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate is a well-established reaction in organic chemistry. Cooper et al. (2017, Angew. Chem.) confirmed non-enzymatic decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids at moderate temperatures. Novikov & Copley (2013, PNAS) studied metal-ion catalyzed decarboxylation of \u03b1-keto acids. Under hydrothermal conditions (T > 100\u00b0C), the half-life of pyruvate decarboxylation is on the order of hours, making this reaction highly plausible."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type C\u2082 oxygenate formation"}, "mechanism": "CO undergoes chain growth on the magnetite surface: CO inserts into a surface methyl (from prior CO hydrogenation), and the resulting C\u2082 acyl intermediate is hydrogenated and released as acetaldehyde. This is a well-characterized FTT product in the C\u2082 oxygenate fraction.", "reasoning": "Rushdi & Simoneit (2001, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) detected C\u2082 oxygenates including acetaldehyde among FTT products on magnetite at 175\u00b0C. McCollom et al. (1999) demonstrated FTT synthesis of oxygenated organics on iron minerals under hydrothermal conditions. Acetaldehyde is a standard FTT product in the Anderson-Schulz-Flory distribution of oxygenates. This provides an independent route to acetaldehyde that does not require pyruvate."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (concentrates reactants on surface)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "dilute aqueous solution with dissolved HCN and NH\u2083, clay surfaces concentrate and orient reactants"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde (CH\u2083CH(OH)CHO) reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine (CH\u2083CH(OH)CH=NH). HCN then performs nucleophilic addition to the imine carbon, yielding the \u03b1-aminonitrile: CH\u2083CH(OH)CH(NH\u2082)CN (threonine aminonitrile). The Strecker mechanism preserves the \u03b2-hydroxyl group, giving the threonine skeleton. Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants via adsorption.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the most widely accepted prebiotic amino acid synthesis routes (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). Wollrab & Ott (2011, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated that Strecker synthesis of hydroxy amino acids (including threonine) from hydroxy aldehydes is efficient under aqueous prebiotic conditions. Lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 yields threonine aminonitrile with the correct carbon skeleton. Montmorillonite catalysis of Strecker reactions was shown by Bujdak & Rode (1999)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_020", "mol_003"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required; acid or base catalysis accelerates", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm acidic or neutral aqueous solution; can proceed in warm pool or tidal flat"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of threonine aminonitrile undergoes sequential hydrolysis: -CN + H\u2082O \u2192 -CONH\u2082 (amide intermediate), then -CONH\u2082 + H\u2082O \u2192 -COOH + NH\u2083. The two-step hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile to the \u03b1-amino acid (threonine) with release of NH\u2083. The amino group at the \u03b1-carbon is retained throughout.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is a well-characterized reaction in prebiotic chemistry. Miller & Van Trump (1981) demonstrated efficient hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids under mildly acidic aqueous conditions. The reaction proceeds at room temperature over days to weeks, or more rapidly at elevated temperatures. This is the standard terminal step of the Strecker amino acid synthesis pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Strecker synthesis: formaldehyde to glycine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm pool with dissolved HCN, NH\u2083, HCHO"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form methyleneimine (H\u2082C=NH), which undergoes nucleophilic addition by HCN to give aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CN), the glycine aminonitrile. This is the simplest Strecker reaction producing the simplest amino acid precursor.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde, HCN, and NH\u2083 was demonstrated in the original Miller-Urey experiment context (Miller, 1957, Biochim. Biophys. Acta) and is one of the most robust prebiotic amino acid synthesis reactions. Danger et al. (2012, Chem. Soc. Rev.) reviewed the Strecker mechanism in prebiotic contexts. Glycine aminonitrile was identified as a key intermediate by Peltzer et al. (1984)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Hydrolysis of glycine aminonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (mild acid sites catalyze hydrolysis)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm pool, acidic clay surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Glycine aminonitrile (H\u2082N-CH\u2082-CN) undergoes two-step hydrolysis: the nitrile is converted first to the amide (glycinamide) and then to the free carboxylic acid (glycine) with release of NH\u2083. Montmorillonite acid sites catalyze the hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis is well-established (Miller & Van Trump, 1981). Bujdak & Rode (1999, J. Mol. Evol.) showed that montmorillonite catalyzes both Strecker and aminonitrile hydrolysis reactions. The hydrolysis half-life is days to weeks at 25\u00b0C and hours at elevated temperatures."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Glycine-acetaldehyde aldol condensation to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_020", "mol_004"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite or divalent metal ions (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated pool, mineral surface catalysis, mildly alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "Glycine, activated as a Schiff base or via its \u03b1-carbanion equivalent, undergoes aldol addition to acetaldehyde. The \u03b1-carbon of glycine (deprotonated under basic conditions or metal-ion mediated) attacks the carbonyl of acetaldehyde, forming the C-C bond and yielding threonine directly. This is the reverse of the biological threonine aldolase reaction. Divalent metal ions (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) or pyridoxal-like cofactors stabilize the glycine carbanion.", "reasoning": "Weber (2001, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) proposed and demonstrated that amino acid aldol reactions are plausible prebiotic routes to \u03b2-hydroxy amino acids. The reverse threonine aldolase reaction (glycine + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine) is thermodynamically feasible under concentrated conditions. Pizzarello (2006, Acc. Chem. Res.) discussed the formation of threonine and other complex amino acids via aldol chemistry. Metal-ion catalyzed aldol reactions between amino acids and aldehydes have been demonstrated by Cleaves (2008). Montmorillonite provides both concentration effects and Lewis acid catalysis."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Methylglyoxal cyanohydrin formation and hydrolysis to 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline aqueous solution favoring cyanohydrin formation"}, "mechanism": "HCN performs nucleophilic addition to the aldehyde carbon (C1) of methylglyoxal (CH\u2083-CO-CHO), forming the cyanohydrin CH\u2083-CO-CH(OH)-CN. The cyanohydrin is regioselective for the aldehyde over the ketone because the aldehyde is more electrophilic and less sterically hindered. The nitrile then undergoes hydrolysis (CN \u2192 CONH\u2082 \u2192 COOH) in aqueous solution to yield 3-hydroxy-2-oxobutanoic acid (2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate): CH\u2083-CO-CH(OH)-COOH. The overall transformation adds a carboxyl group at C1 while preserving the C2 ketone.", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation from HCN and aldehydes is one of the most well-established reactions in prebiotic chemistry (Schlesinger & Miller, 1983). The regioselectivity for aldehyde over ketone attack by cyanide is well-documented in organic chemistry and ensures the correct product regiochemistry. Powner et al. (2009, Nature) exploited cyanohydrin chemistry in prebiotic nucleotide synthesis. The subsequent nitrile hydrolysis is the same mechanism as in Strecker synthesis (Miller & Van Trump, 1981). This two-step sequence converts the C3 methylglyoxal into a C4 \u03b1-keto acid suitable for reductive amination."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Reductive amination of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_020", "mol_004"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-380K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "FeS (mackinawite), with Fe\u00b2\u207a ions in solution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing hydrothermal-influenced pool, Fe\u00b2\u207a-rich"}, "mechanism": "The C2 ketone of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate (CH\u2083CH(OH)COCOOH) condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine at C2, which is then reduced by H\u2082 on the FeS surface to yield the amine. The product is threonine: CH\u2083CH(OH)CH(NH\u2082)COOH. FeS provides the reducing equivalents and the surface for the heterogeneous hydrogenation of the imine intermediate.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces is experimentally demonstrated by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Lett.) and Barge et al. (2019, PNAS). Muchowska et al. (2019, Nature) showed reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on Fe\u2070, establishing the principle for all \u03b1-keto acid to amino acid conversions. The 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate substrate preserves the \u03b2-hydroxyl during reductive amination because only the C2 keto group reacts with NH\u2083. This provides a direct non-Strecker route to threonine."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Primary Strecker via formose + formamide-derived HCN", "description": "CO\u2082 is fixed to formate (greigite) and CO (magnetite) in hydrothermal vents. CO is converted to formaldehyde via FTT synthesis. Formate is amidated to formamide, which is photolyzed to HCN on the surface. Formaldehyde enters the formose network (glycolaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde \u2192 methylglyoxal), methylglyoxal is selectively reduced to lactaldehyde on greigite, and Strecker synthesis with HCN + NH\u2083 gives threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_014", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_008"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Primary Strecker via formose + hydrothermal HCN", "description": "Same formose route to lactaldehyde as P1, but HCN is produced directly in the hydrothermal vent from NH\u2083 + CO on pyrite at high temperature. This provides a purely hydrothermal-then-surface pathway without requiring UV photolysis for HCN.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_014", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Glycine aldol with pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde + formamide HCN", "description": "Formaldehyde (from FTT) and HCN (from formamide UV decomposition) undergo Strecker synthesis to glycine. Independently, CO\u2082 is fixed to pyruvate on native iron, which thermally decarboxylates to acetaldehyde. Glycine and acetaldehyde undergo aldol condensation on mineral surfaces to directly yield threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_017", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Glycine aldol with FTT acetaldehyde + formamide HCN", "description": "Glycine is formed via Strecker synthesis (as in P3). Acetaldehyde is produced independently via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis from CO + H\u2082 on magnetite, bypassing the pyruvate intermediate. Glycine + acetaldehyde undergo aldol condensation to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_013", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_017", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Glycine aldol with pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde + hydrothermal HCN", "description": "All C\u2081 and nitrogen chemistry occurs in hydrothermal vents: CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde (FTT), NH\u2083 + CO \u2192 HCN (pyrite), CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (Fe\u2070) \u2192 acetaldehyde. On the surface, formaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083 \u2192 glycine (Strecker). In biochemical assembly, glycine + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine (aldol).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_017", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Glycine aldol with FTT acetaldehyde + hydrothermal HCN", "description": "Entirely hydrothermal C1 chemistry: formaldehyde and acetaldehyde both from FTT, HCN from NH\u2083 + CO on pyrite. Surface Strecker gives glycine. Biochemical aldol gives threonine. The most hydrothermal-dominated pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_013", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_017", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Reductive amination via methylglyoxal cyanohydrin + formamide HCN", "description": "Formose route produces methylglyoxal (as in P1). HCN from formamide photolysis attacks methylglyoxal aldehyde to form a cyanohydrin, which hydrolyzes to 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate. Reductive amination of this \u03b1-keto acid on FeS yields threonine directly, bypassing the Strecker aminonitrile route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_019", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_008", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Reductive amination via methylglyoxal cyanohydrin + hydrothermal HCN", "description": "Same formose/methylglyoxal route as P7, but HCN is sourced from high-temperature NH\u2083 + CO reaction on pyrite. Cyanohydrin formation, hydrolysis, and reductive amination proceed as in P7.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_019", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_005", "mol_012", "mol_008", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Strecker via pyruvate-acetaldehyde reroute to methylglyoxal alternative", "description": "CO\u2082 is fixed to pyruvate on Fe\u2070, which decarboxylates to acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is oxidized to glycolaldehyde... wait, this doesn't work cleanly. Instead: Pyruvate decarboxylation gives acetaldehyde; independently formose gives glycolaldehyde. Both feed into glyceraldehyde synthesis when formaldehyde is available. However, this pathway distinguishes itself by using pyruvate as an indicator of metabolic relevance and connects to the formose network through its decarboxylation product acetaldehyde which, along with glycine from Strecker, provides an alternative aldol route. Additionally: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde; formaldehyde from FTT; HCN from formamide; glycine Strecker; glycine + acetaldehyde \u2192 threonine. This pathway emphasizes the pyruvate hub and the convergence of metabolic and synthetic routes.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Fully convergent: dual HCN sources to Strecker threonine", "description": "Both HCN production routes operate simultaneously: formamide UV photolysis (surface) and NH\u2083 + CO on pyrite (hydrothermal), feeding into a common HCN pool. Formaldehyde from FTT enters the formose cascade to yield methylglyoxal, which is selectively reduced to lactaldehyde. The converged HCN + NH\u2083 + lactaldehyde undergo Strecker synthesis to threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine. This pathway represents maximum redundancy in nitrogen delivery.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_014", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_014", "mol_015"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Formaldehyde: central C\u2081 building block for all pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_014", "rxn_016"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "HCN: nitrogen carrier produced by two independent routes, consumed in three distinct reactions", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014", "rxn_016", "rxn_019"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Methylglyoxal: key C\u2083 dicarbonyl at the branch point between Strecker (via lactaldehyde) and reductive amination (via cyanohydrin) routes to threonine", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_019"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Pyruvate: central metabolic hub linking CO\u2082 fixation to acetaldehyde production for glycine aldol pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "description": "Acetaldehyde: C\u2082 building block produced by two independent routes (pyruvate decarboxylation and FTT), feeding into the glycine aldol route to threonine", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_018"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 553360.6960773468, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T00:34:19.999369", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: Three distinct terminal routes to threonine converge from prebiotically plausible intermediates: (1) Strecker synthesis from lactaldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083, (2) aldol condensation of glycine + acetaldehyde (reverse threonine aldolase), and (3) reductive amination of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate. Lactaldehyde is obtained by selective reduction of methylglyoxal, which derives from glyceraldehyde dehydration in the formose network. Formaldehyde (central C1 hub) is produced by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite. HCN is produced by two independent routes: formamide UV decomposition and high-temperature NH\u2083 + CO reaction on pyrite. Acetaldehyde is produced by two independent routes: pyruvate thermal decarboxylation and FTT synthesis. Environmental flow is unidirectional: Hydrothermal (CO\u2082 fixation, C1 chemistry, reductions) \u2192 Surface (formose, Strecker, photochemistry) \u2192 Biochemical (final assembly, hydrolysis). This avoids unrealistic environmental bouncing while maintaining cross-environment connectivity through transported intermediates (formate, formaldehyde, CO, acetaldehyde, methylglyoxal).\n\nMOLECULES (20 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_005: CO (carbon monoxide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_006: CHOO- (formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C3H4O2 (methylglyoxal) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H6O2 (lactaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C2H4N2 (glycine aminonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C2H5NO2 (glycine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_018: C4H6N2O (threonine aminonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_019: C4H6O4 (2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_020: C4H9NO3 (threonine) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (20 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_006 (CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_005, mol_004 (Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_005, mol_002 -> mol_009 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_006, mol_003 -> mol_007, mol_004 (Formamide synthesis from formate and ammonia) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_007 -> mol_008, mol_004 (UV photolysis of formamide to HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_003, mol_005 -> mol_008, mol_004 (High-temperature HCN synthesis from NH\u2083 and CO) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_007: mol_009, mol_009 -> mol_010 (Formose self-condensation: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_010, mol_009 -> mol_011 (Aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde \u2192 glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_011 -> mol_012, mol_004 (Glyceraldehyde dehydration to methylglyoxal) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_012, mol_002 -> mol_013 (Selective reduction of methylglyoxal to lactaldehyde on FeS) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_011: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_014, mol_004 (Direct CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on native iron) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_012: mol_014 -> mol_015, mol_001 (Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_013: mol_005, mol_002 -> mol_015 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_014: mol_013, mol_008, mol_003 -> mol_018, mol_004 (Strecker synthesis: lactaldehyde to threonine aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_015: mol_018, mol_004 -> mol_020, mol_003 (Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_016: mol_009, mol_008, mol_003 -> mol_016, mol_004 (Strecker synthesis: formaldehyde to glycine aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_017: mol_016, mol_004 -> mol_017, mol_003 (Hydrolysis of glycine aminonitrile to glycine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_018: mol_017, mol_015 -> mol_020, mol_004 (Glycine-acetaldehyde aldol condensation to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_019: mol_012, mol_008, mol_004 -> mol_019 (Methylglyoxal cyanohydrin formation and hydrolysis to 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate) [Surface]\n  - rxn_020: mol_019, mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_020, mol_004 (Reductive amination of 2-keto-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Primary Strecker via formose + formamide-derived HCN (11 steps)\n  - P2: Primary Strecker via formose + hydrothermal HCN (9 steps)\n  - P3: Glycine aldol with pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde + formamide HCN (10 steps)\n  - P4: Glycine aldol with FTT acetaldehyde + formamide HCN (9 steps)\n  - P5: Glycine aldol with pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde + hydrothermal HCN (8 steps)\n  - P6: Glycine aldol with FTT acetaldehyde + hydrothermal HCN (7 steps)\n  - P7: Reductive amination via methylglyoxal cyanohydrin + formamide HCN (10 steps)\n  - P8: Reductive amination via methylglyoxal cyanohydrin + hydrothermal HCN (8 steps)\n  - P9: Strecker via pyruvate-acetaldehyde reroute to methylglyoxal alternative (10 steps)\n  - P10: Fully convergent: dual HCN sources to Strecker threonine (12 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_009, mol_008, mol_012, mol_014, mol_015\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\