\"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.75,\n      \"feedback\": \"Interesting alternative route through keto-acid intermediate. The cyanohydrin formation (rxn_019) is chemically reasonable but lumps two steps (cyanohydrin + hydrolysis) into one node. Reductive amination (rxn_020) is plausible with Fe\u00b2\u207a/FeS as reductant but the stereoselectivity and chemoselectivity are uncertain\u2014competing side reactions likely. Avoids the methylglyoxal\u2192lactaldehyde environmental bounce since rxn_019 operates at Surface.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Split rxn_019 into explicit cyanohydrin formation and nitrile hydrolysis steps\",\n        \"Specify the reducing agent and conditions for reductive amination in rxn_020\",\n        \"Consider whether pyridoxal-type cofactors could assist the reductive amination prebiotically\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_020\": 0.65\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"More streamlined version of P7 with hydrothermal HCN. Better environmental flow. The reductive amination remains the weakest step, but the pathway provides a chemically distinct route to threonine that complements the Strecker pathways.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_020\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Strengthen rxn_020 with specific mineral catalyst and literature precedent for prebiotic reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.80\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.72,\n      \"feedback\": \"This reroute through pyruvate-to-acetaldehyde as an alternative intermediate adds redundancy but does not resolve the core environmental bounce issue. The pathway is circuitous and the pyruvate-to-acetaldehyde detour doesn't add chemical value to the Strecker terminus compared to P1/P2.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"This pathway adds complexity without clear benefit; consider pruning in favor of P1/P2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.80\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"Fully convergent pathway merging both HCN sources into the Strecker route. The dual HCN sourcing provides robustness\u2014if one source is intermittent, the other compensates. Longest pathway but captures the full network topology. Same rxn_010 environmental bounce issue inherited from P1/P2.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"The convergence of dual HCN sources is a strength worth preserving in network design\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-designed synthesis network with excellent topology and strategic diversity. Three distinct terminal routes to threonine (Strecker, aldol, reductive amination) provide genuine chemical alternatives rather than trivial variants. The C1 chemistry backbone (CO\u2082 \u2192 CO \u2192 CH\u2082O \u2192 formose \u2192 methylglyoxal) is prebiotically grounded and the hub molecule selection is appropriate. Key strengths: (1) Dual HCN sources add robustness, (2) formose-derived C3 intermediates are well-precedented, (3) multiple convergence points create a true network rather than a tree. Key weaknesses: (1) The methylglyoxal \u2192 lactaldehyde reduction (rxn_010) requires Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal transport, violating the claimed unidirectional flow\u2014this affects all Strecker pathways. (2) The glycine-acetaldehyde aldol (rxn_018) is thermodynamically disfavored without enzyme catalysis, undermining 4 of 10 pathways. (3) Some FTT steps (rxn_003, rxn_013) lack specificity regarding yields and selectivity. (4) Surface reactions could benefit from explicit mineral specifications (e.g., borate for formose stabilization, montmorillonite for Strecker). Despite these issues, the Strecker route via P2 reaches the threshold for approval, and the overall network architecture is sound and prebiotically coherent.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.83,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.85\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_004": 0.7, "rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_002": 0.85, "rxn_003": 0.7, "rxn_